{"dataset": "promcon", "note_file": "02-Sources/PromCon/2016-2016-berlin/Sessions/welcome-and-introduction.md", "title": "Welcome and Introduction", "youtube_url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-JkxB0CiMjU", "youtube_id": "-JkxB0CiMjU", "youtube_title": "PromCon 2016: Welcome and Introduction - Julius Volz", "video_match_score": 0.788, "transcript_file": "_sources/transcripts/youtube-enriched/promcon/2016/welcome-and-introduction/-JkxB0CiMjU.txt", "transcript_chars": 8580, "transcript_summary": "does that work yeah good morning glad you're all here I hope you're enjoying the view I'm you're on I'm just a random person for now we curse among here to introduce you to Julia's folds founder of Prometheus and organizer from Khan one of the founders in one of the organizers thanks so much for come for coming and welcome it's so exciting that the room is actually full now after half a year of you know trying to get everything into order so I want to thank everyone for coming but also I want to thank everyone who has ever contributed to prometheus whether it's a PR or you open an issue for some bug or you helped someone on IRC or maybe you're just pushing Prometheus in your company or maybe you're giving talks somewhere like that's like all of this wouldn't have been possible without all your efforts so thank you so much for that and also thanks so much for the people who are the core maintained errs of Prometheus these days I'm more you know freelancing around it and not doing so much on the upstream project right now more community stuff so thank you so much to them as well I want to give a bit of perspective to you know how we got here four years ago Prometheus got started when Matt and I joined soundcloud from google and we had the problem there that we already had a dynamic environment they're kind of like uber natus like cluster scheduler where everything is floating around dynamically but we had monitoring tools that were made more for this kind of static age of things so we had graphite stats d ganglia and so on and they just didn't really cut it anymore for tracking down what was happening especially in an outage or when you want to Canary something and we looked at the open source monitoring tools that existed and didn't really find one that we could extend in the way that we would be happy with it maybe we were a bit crazy also but so we started Prometheus started using it inside soundcloud for a while then gathered some first friends and all side users and contributors but didn't really make a lot of noise about it this changed in the beginning of last year in January where we felt okay the system is ready and mature enough to present it to a wider world let's whip up a nice home page and we published a series of blog posts about it try to get on hacker news that didn't really work out at first by ourselves I mean I think we if we got to the front page then only somewhere at the bottom but then two weeks later someone who we didn't even know put it on Hacker News it ended up on place number one and since then the growth suddenly really exploded like we could see people flooding into our IC channel the pull request and the mailing list and so on so this is kind of the public birth of Prometheus i would say then some companies started using it it became more and more mature we got contributors from all kinds of companies but then the question kind of came what's the governance of prometheus so is there the soundcloud still controlling it is it an independent project or is there may be one prometheus company behind it that ultimately dictates its fate it might make some features closed source so for people who are worried about that we were also thinking okay maybe we should found some kind of foundation or find one that is willing to take us in luckily around that time their cloud native foundation the cloud native computing foundation was founded as a sub foundation of the Linux Foundation and in May this year we joined them after a bit of negotiation and we joined after the second as the second member project after KU Benitez so we feel in really great company with this kind of dynamic systems and we are for monitoring those and this is kind of sending a signal to people that prometheus is an independent open source project not you know controlled by one company then there was still in the room that we were still zero dot something and you know when you upgraded prometheus you often had the problem that config file options changed or the storage from it in the beginning you can changed sometimes the HTTP API you were never really sure you have to check the change lock so in July just bit more than a month ago we release the first stable version of prometheus so that gives people really signal that they can use Prometheus and build on it without worrying about so many update hurdles anymore then finally what's the last step we need for success is of course a conference and that's happening today this is not really time proportional you see like most of the stuff and most of the stuff is happening more towards the end so I started thinking about prom Khan in February primary six of this year so it's been half a year of organizing that and now some people helped me out as well Brian especially with helping handling all the financials with this company robust perception thanks for that it's been an amazing ride and now we're actually here I want to show a funny graph of the most important stat what's the most important stats for any open source project of course get up stars so I mean that's a bit of a joke of course but I like this graph because it shows the history of the project of it so you see in 2012 and the at the end of it we threw it on github we didn't tell anyone then some people started using it and you know there's a tiny bit of growth then hacker news happened and then it just it's going up still and it looks like the line is more than linear growth which is great sign so in terms of the ecosystem we have more than 250 people contributing code to the official repose in the prometheus github org and more than 50 exporters and other kind of third-party integrations just in the last quarter alone we had more than 350 articles about prometheus or mentioning Prometheus and companies that are using Prometheus are a really impressive list these are just you know some that you might recognize but there are so many others like hundreds of others small ones big ones and we've been totally blown away by that so that's for you know what we need is how we got there basically in back to some organizational stuff for this conference please we encourage you to tweet about the conference the hashtag is prom con 2016 with the number in there feel free to mention our twitter account as well there are lightning talks on both days from 5 30 p.m. to six pm the signup board is right there you can just write yourself in if there's still a slot free we already have a bunch of them in there so they're all five minutes long don't take longer please so looking forward there's an evening event today it's about 10 minutes walk from here so in that direction it's an outside area which is really nice we have both inside and outside options but today I think it's going to be so hot that outside is great and the drinks are sponsored by a chorus so thank you very much for that there's also going to be food there so you know we have breakfast lunch both days and dinner today at this evening event there's also map in the schedule that shows you how to get there but we probably will just walk together there and hopefully know what you will get lost user service so Brian is collecting user surveys from companies using prometheus and then we'll publish those on the prometheus blog they are already three or so and we'll publish some more but if you want your company and their usage of prometheus featured on there please write to brine or just approach them in person there's a code of conduct so we want to make this a pleasant and harassment free conference for everyone so please please please read it and follow it if you have a concern please approach either me directly or someone else who has a green staff badge finally big big big thanks to our sponsors on one hand is really cool because it shows interest of companies in prometheus on the other hand it wouldn't have been possible to create this conference in this way without them there's so many costly items the catering the venue sponsored by Google and then the professional video recordings evening party all that the schwag wouldn't have been possible without their help so thanks a lot finally the program is really packed there's talks from small companies big companies i think the farthest away traveled speaker is from japan we have an attendee from indonesia as well so that's really cool really exciting and yeah so actually the next talk is me again so i think beyond well actually not announce me but i'm saying thanks for now I'm taking like a one-minute break thanks for having", "keywords": ["prometheus", "thanks", "companies", "please", "company", "started", "foundation", "conference", "actually", "without", "source", "everyone", "someone", "wouldn", "possible", "around", "joined", "soundcloud"], "status": "transcript-downloaded"}
{"dataset": "promcon", "note_file": "02-Sources/PromCon/2016-2016-berlin/Sessions/prometheus-design-and-philosophy.md", "title": "Prometheus Design and Philosophy", "youtube_url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4DzoajMs4DM", "youtube_id": "4DzoajMs4DM", "youtube_title": "PromCon 2016: Prometheus Design and Philosophy - Why It Is the Way It Is - Julius Volz", "video_match_score": 0.696, "transcript_file": "_sources/transcripts/youtube-enriched/promcon/2016/prometheus-design-and-philosophy/4DzoajMs4DM.txt", "transcript_chars": 20482, "transcript_summary": "uh all right um so uh I want to talk a bit about why Prometheus is the way it is as an opener for the conference or the second opener um as you might have known uh as you might have um experienced when you're coming from a different type of monitoring system like graphite or nagos gangas STD and so on um Prometheus does a lot of things very differently and sometimes that can lead to a bit of a culture Clash uh might take a while to understand why it does things differently and sometimes you might also think wow that's really a stupid way to do it why did they do it like that can isn't there a better way um so I just want to go into some of these decisions and show a bit our thinking behind them and why we think they're good uh approaches and principles so just as a disclaimer it's all kind of our opinionated way of looking at things we don't have to be right in every way and maybe don't fit to every use case but there is some thought behind everything as a perspective what is Prometheus really Prometheus is a Time series based monitoring system and it tries to cover the whole bread like from uh instrumentation getting metrics out of your processes storing them querying them and then doing useful stuff with them you know like graphs at hog debugging and so on and we really focused on two use cases back then really out of necessity which were we need needed operational systems monitoring so really a live view of what's happening in your system um and uh specifically it really needed to work for dynamic Cloud environments so these were kind of the pain points uh we were trying to solve um so this Focus means that we willfully really ignore some other use cases which we really do not intend to solve so if you want to for example store logs or raw events of something you use something like elastic search if you want to trace an individual user request through uh a stack of microservices use something like zipin and we don't do magic style anomaly detection you know that kind of fancy machine learning data mining statistics um we really only do explicit uh queries uh no durable long-term storage in Prometheus itself though there might be a decoupled way of doing that in the future um and so since we only have a local storage in every Prometheus server there's no automatic horizontal scaling either of course uh we're kind of ping on user and authentication features which are kind of Enterprise features from our view but I'll also go into that more later so let's talk about the first feature of Prometheus which is maybe one of the least controversial ones so I just want to talk about it briefly it's the data model um but it is different so uh as you might know like there were monitoring systems before that had a completely flat metric uh model but then there were ones that had a hierarchical model like graphite and statd um which you can see on the right here where you organize your metric in kind of a tree and every component of the tree uh is one of the dimensions in a semi in a more in an implicit way and um the label based dimensional data model that we chose in Prometheus you can see on the left and there you have more like this explicit way of saying uh what every Dimension means and you can also access very U flexibly by any Dimension so the problem with the hierarchical data model is that often you know let's look at a query um with the label-based data model you just select exactly the labels that you care about and you don't really care where in the hierarchy they live um and with the hierarchical data model you still kind of need to know what dimensions exist and start them away and um for every job or service the hierarchy might also have totally different meanings so what if you wanted to do something like show me all the jobs that have a Handler of Slash tracks or so um then you're kind of inverting your hierarchy tree and maybe the monitoring system isn't even indexed in such a way to be able to do that efficiently so we think that this kind of label based data model um is really nice and it allows for efficient crosscutting selection um and it's also very explicit around what means what what the different components mean so next up the query language we don't have a SQL like query language and sometimes there are questions around that why that is um because SQL you know that's kind of standard data analysts know how to use SQL and you know you should use SQL if you can or some kind of dialect but let's look at some examples of what you might want to do in Prometheus and how they would look in promql and SQL in a SQL like dialect so one thing might be just taking the rate of a counter over the last five minutes that's what it looks like in promql in a SQL light dialect that I'm making up it could look like this um so one thing you see is Prometheus automatically selects all the labels that are output by a given expression and in a SQL way usually you have to select them all I could use a star here but then it might double select the value of which we only want the rate so then you kind of need to know what dimensions are there you need to select them uh it's a bit longer the metric name could become a table still not too bad right uh or taking the average temperature by city in a country that's what it looks like in promql still not too too bad in the SQL like language um but what about binary operations which I think is one case where Prometheus really shines um where you have one vector of Time series on one side of the binary operation whether it's a plus minus divided or whatever um and another Vector on the other side and they're automatically matched on exactly identical label sets um and then propagated into the output for calculating ratios or differences this very useful all the time so I think not sure but I think in a SQL like dialect this would look kind of like this I omitted some stuff because it would have gotten too long um because now you kind of have to say exactly on what labels to join you need to know what labels exactly are there um and then what to show in the output um so I think uh in my opinion that promql is a better choice for uh this kind of metrix computation that we do and also we designed it from the beginning to be a readon language and we're doing writes through a more efficient input path um out of band so um kind of saying select for every query uh would be a bit Superfluous um my local monitor here turned off but maybe I just need to press this button well I don't know oh I can see that one um so my my next favorite topic is the pull versus push debate so this kind of um creates some worry in people sometimes you know why don't you push I like pushing more my firewall likes pushing more um but we think there's that there's a lot of uh benefits that you have in a pool based world and I first want to go a bit into into the benefits um so pull really is your friend in in my opinion um when you're monitoring ing system goes out and scrapes all the targets directly then it already has one signal for health monitoring for very basic health monitoring so if it cannot scrape a given Target you automatically get a synthetic up time series with a value of zero which you can use for upness alerting uh so your monitoring system in this case has a signal for that already um pull allows what we like to call horizontal monitoring actually that's a term that I learned recently from Brian um where when you have two teams and they have different services and you know they have totally you know their own stacks of monitoring and everything and maybe one team now wants to pull some metrics from the other team uh in a push-based world you would now the other team would have to configure all the instances to push to two monitoring systems um but only the right instances and so it's kind of more setup worries and in the pool world you just say oh well you know I'm just going to pull that service into my monor Monitoring Service as well of course you maybe should still talk to the other team that that's okay but otherwise that other infrastructure doesn't even need to know about that about the fact that you're there and you want something from them so in generally poll is more flexible uh this also shows uh when you just run uh a test server on your laptop and you can scrape all production data to test new recording rules or some other kind of new monitoring setup you can run um two identic configured Prometheus servers to get high availability um at least for the kind of most recent data and for alerting one will always be there and uh one funny complaint is that when uh when people are worrying about a pool-based monitoring system they think well then it's a lot of work I need to configure my monitoring system to know about everything that's out there uh and then I said well you kind of probably need that anyways like if your monitoring system is going to tell you that something is wrong in the world at least for most use cases um you kind of want to know what the things out there uh should look like and what should be there um so my argument would be you need that kind of configuration anyways and uh but in the push based world now you need exra configuration you need to tell the individual processes that are pushing to a monitoring system what their identity is in terms of what service they belong to and what instance they are so you can track them down later and they also need to know where the monitoring system lives um so it's actually in total I would say more configuration needed with a push based approach and yes uh P pull scales at least for the use cases that that we care about normally um I wrote a blog post about that it's on Prometheus IO blog I think the last post that's on there in case you're interested in that but I have a firewall or or you know there's people who have some Network segments that are file worlded off or they there's internet of things people who have devices you know in people's homes and obviously you can't just like pull from people's home networks tell them to open a port on their plastic routers um so admittedly that's not exactly the use case that promethus was designed for um again we were designed more for uh monitoring your data center infrastructure but still often you can have you can make some kind of workarounds or use some alternatives to still make these use cases work um one thing we always recommend in any case is to run your monitoring as close as possible to your targets because then you have less uh possibilities of disruption in between kind of would be worse in all categories um it's it's still easy to construct but not as easy um we don't really care so much about ease of parsing because the parsing is usually done by the Promethea server although we have like a little adapter that if you really want to get Json format that's possible um but yeah I mean it's less efficient you usually have to pass the entire request body with ajason object before you can start processing it and I would argue that the text format is also a bit more readable although that's obviously subjective so in the end we decided that Jason as yet another like third protocol didn't really it didn't really make sense for us to support that um we don't have clustering in Prometheus meaning um we only have a a local storage um that has some you know limited retention we don't really do durability but now you're thinking well it's this kind of clustered Dynamic modern world shouldn't everything that's being built nowadays be horizontally scalable and clustered and durable well clustered systems are first of all really really hard to get right they might take years until you iron out all the Kinks and then uh a clustered system might be the first thing that goes down when you really need it so when you need your monitoring maybe the network is just having some partition or it's having problems and now your clustered monitoring system doesn't answer queries anymore uh in the kind of model that Prometheus chose you would just run multiple identical prometh servers as long as you can still reach one of those you should be fine so we really wanted to keep the design simple it's not just because we're lazy um and focus on this aspect of live operational monitoring um and yeah as I said ha is still easy to do in that way relabeling our our friend so who has used relabeling in Prometheus already oh okay about half of people uh who has had the kind of WTF reaction when they first saw it uh maybe a fourth of hands or so okay yeah totally understandable um so relabeling for the people who have not been exposed to uh yet um is a small domain specific language that is part of the configuration file where when you configure a certain service Discovery mechanism to give you very raw targets with raw metadata information to then apply a series of filter and transformation steps to them to say which targets you actually want want to Monitor and how so this example I don't know how many people can read it but I lifted that from a Prometheus service Discovery example um uh from a kubernetes service Discovery example and so raw kubernetes targets are coming in in the first step we're saying okay please only scrape instances that have a Prometheus IO scrape annotation with a value of true and we drop all others um then if the kubernetes annotations have a special scheme for us to scrape the Target on we also configure a special underscore underscore scheme label and so on which are kind of these underscore underscore internal labels are ones that will be invisible later and only used during this kind of relabeling phase uh we do a similar thing for the metric path we uh do a similar thing for the port and then we choose to map all the uh service labels that kubernetes has for the instance uh into uh into our time series Target labels and we do the same with the kubernetes name space and service name so this this options of you know mapping labels transforming labels uh selecting labels uh targets and so it it has a bit of a steep learning curve but it's very flexible now the question is the alternative what would that be and the alternative I think would have been worse because if you wanted to enable this for every different service discovery type that's out there there would be a million new uh partially uh inconsistent config options that will all have to be maintained documented and understood so uh and then we might not even cover all the use cases that are possible with relabeling so we thought of course relabeling is a bit of a mind Bender at at first but it's probably um the Lesser evil um and we hope it's useful like once you understand it it's usually really cool our client libraries are a bit different than others you might be used to uh if you look at examples like the statsd client Library it has no State at all uh when a request happens you send out a UDP packet like get rid of the state immediately don't bother me with that um that's cool that you don't need state but then you immediately need to send everything over the network uh takes more work than you might need actually in Prometheus it's a bit different the client leavs client libraries keep a bit of State for you but not a lot like they don't actually record raw events or logs or so for you and then you have to worry about memory growing they just count up stuff in memory and when Prometheus comes along um you know it just pulls the latest state so you get way way way uh smaller monitoring traffic and if you're counting hundreds of thousands of events per second that might actually also get really really relevant from an efficiency standpoint and uh for the counters engagers it might not be that important but for the two more complex history um metric types that we have the histogram and the summary the client libraries also do some kind of semi complicated management and bookkeeping for you um that would be really annoying to replicate yourself and like for over all the metric types it also care takes care of the labeling for you and and remembers all the latest state of the dimensional time series so the client lips are a bit more a bit fatter than a completely dumb protocol serializer in Prometheus but there's a good reason for this everything in Prometheus is a float 64 all the sample values who has been bugged by that before anyone nobody here uh but maybe wondered about why it is that way one person um I mean it's crazy right why I store everything is float 64s what I only need integers and I just want to count up requests um what about Precision Precision do I get something like two. z001 uh can that happen um so first of all it's just simpler we're lazy and you know simpler system is better uh can have fewer bugs and you need to care less about type conversions and so on so is it only that reason not really um if you're worried about size um it's really not the problem the way uh our storage stores it both in memory and on disk is if something is actually an integer value it gets compressed really really really well um even if you have uh mixed data floats and inches and so on uh with a new vbit encoding uh you get uh an average size per sample and time stamp of 1.3 bytes if you only have integers it would be way smaller even um and the good thing is you don't need to worry about Precision with float 64s until uh 2 to the power of 53 that means that you can store um consecutive integers in the float 64 without any loss of inter integer Precision or funky floating Point stuff happening to you until that number and what that means in practice is to run into trouble you would need to increment a counter 1 million times a second for 285 years um there are some Fringe use cases where this could happen but normally people should not worry about this or restart their instances every couple of years um this is really only about counters usually where you worry about this right so normally this is really not a problem and it makes things much simpler finally authentication or multi-user as I said Prometheus doesn't really support those features out of the box um first of all there's just too many different ways of doing them uh both for authentication and for multi-tenancy and when you have authentication then you also need some kind of SSL or TLS and there are so many different ways of configuring TLS and we then would have to expose them in all the different serving components so all the export uh the push Gateway the Prometheus server itself so what we just usually say is you know we focus on great monitoring um it would be too much maintenance overhead to try to maintain all these authentication and user management features and all the components so you can solve all externally in many cases by just putting a reverse proxy in front of things where you can solve it in any way you want so you can set up authentication and TLS options in the way you want with maybe a small engine or similar and with multi- tendency it gets a bit more difficult um because now you have to thread a user ID through the entire system somehow um you can do that with some hacks so for example what uh I heard what some one company does is they have a Gateway in front of Prometheus um where they basically add a tenant label to every time series that's coming in and then when you when uh a user queries through this Gateway this Gateway also makes makes sure uh that um this label is always present so users can only see their data labels were not really designed for that use case but it should work so but then again this is like we have to scope the project to a certain scope and we cannot support everything but let's see what the future brings um so as a conclusion I would say for me it's not specifically about Prometheus that I care about so much but about these thoughts behind the different decisions we made and the best practices for monitoring that result from those um so you know if Prometheus dies tomorrow and there's some totally different monitoring system I'd be happy as long as it still followed a lot of these decisions um and again of course these are our opinion we think they're good opinions but um your your miles may vary and of course they might not apply to every use case but I hope it's been useful to yeah show a bit why promethus is the way it is so thanks a lot and I'm open for [Applause] questions", "keywords": ["prometheus", "monitoring", "labels", "everything", "series", "actually", "authentication", "metric", "usually", "targets", "relabeling", "client", "course", "select", "exactly", "language", "scrape", "clustered"], "status": "transcript-downloaded"}
{"dataset": "promcon", "note_file": "02-Sources/PromCon/2016-2016-berlin/Sessions/prometheus-is-good-for-your-small-startup.md", "title": "Prometheus Is Good for Your Small Startup", "youtube_url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gMHa4Yh8avk", "youtube_id": "gMHa4Yh8avk", "youtube_title": "PromCon 2016: Prometheus Is Good for Your Small Startup - Ignacio P. Carretero", "video_match_score": 0.843, "transcript_file": "_sources/transcripts/youtube-enriched/promcon/2016/prometheus-is-good-for-your-small-startup/gMHa4Yh8avk.txt", "transcript_chars": 23000, "transcript_summary": "uh we've talked about a lot of user cases and a lot of big companies that use prometheus and we are not so i'm gonna explain i'm definitely not an expert i'm not even an expert on prometheus not even on monitoring but i'm gonna tell you how we started to use it and how we are using it which is not perfect and i'm here to learn a lot from you guys but i think it's interesting to well i will explain later so this is me i'm a software developer at shadow cloud uh i'm not really active on twitter but you should definitely follow shuttle tab on shell cloud engineering and we post a lot of some technical discussions because we do some learnings and it's interesting give it a try who we are we are sharecloud we are america a startup founded in in dexter's it's an incubator in new york city you might know it and we were part of it on 2011 we have offices in chicago and madrid and it sounds big but we are actually 15 people and six engineers so that's it we basically uh offer an api for our customers to import email and contacts that's the main idea and our customers usually are isps email address book providers those are some examples before we migrate a lot of edus like harvard and stanford university we have some isps customers like time warner cable or chromecast and even google is a customer of us which we're really proud of it and some facts it's always good to share some facts gmail has already imported three million users using our api we have slas of 99.5 availability so uh we have to be really available and we fulfill them so good for us we move around six terabytes per hour and more than 12 000 migrations per day 12 million emails per day 2.5 million contacts per day well those are number and we support 247 providers so source and destination we move email and contacts from certain destinations from 247 different providers those are the numbers that's it and but as i mentioned we are only six engineers and we're not really we only have someone that's more technical in devops and but yeah we do all of us we do a little bit of everything so what you expect from this presentation i will do first some disclaimers and i'll let you know what we had on the very beginning before we had even the monitoring system so prometheus and what we did we first with prometheus and how it what everything we did wrong and why we did it and how we revamped everything what we have right now and the things we have on our backlog or that we are still working in and things we want to improve uh the disclaimers first i didn't do everything i'm gonna explain so we were six people and all of us we did different things of uh with prometheus monitoring and everything but i'm just here to explain your whole picture obviously and there are a lot of you guys know more than about prometheus and everything i'm gonna explain more than i so i'm not here to tell you how to do things because actually i'm to tell you what we did wrong and you guys should tell me what how we should do things and third yeah i love memes sorry about that i actually removed a lot of them because there were too many but what do we have in the very beginning uh so we were starting we had some instances we're starting to get more projects and we didn't have a monitoring system the first thing we needed was to know if everything was some if the machine was up and down and we had some of automatic scripts chrome based t